Package com.android

  • Interface Summary
    Interface Description
    Behaviour
    Not used in this code
    Flyer
    this is the super interface that Glider inherits from.
    Glider
    this inherits from the functional interface Flyer, but Glider is NOT a functional interface as it inherites the void fly() method, so this interface actually contains two abstract methods
  • Class Summary
    Class Description
    Animal

    Bank<T>
    used with Examples.ex7()
    Cat
    sub class of Animal
    Dog
    sub class of Animal
    Employee<V>
    used with Examples.ex7() and Bank class we create our Employee with a type, e.g Animal, that means that type V will be Animal anywhere inside the Employee
    Examples
    this covers upper and lower bounded wildcards
    Goose
    Class that implements the Glider interface, so it will have to override both void fly() and void glide() methods
    Hanglider
    Class that implements the Glider interface, so it will have to override both void fly() and void glide() methods
    Main
    our main class which contains our main method
    Monkey<T extends Glider>
    Monkey class that has a Generic that can only be a class of obejct that implements the Glider Interface.
    myNumber
    this shows how you can create your own Number wrapper class, however you can't create your own, for instance, Integer class, as each of the built in numeric wrapper types are final not used in this code, just to display that you can create a Number class of your own
    Plane
    class that implements the Flyer interface
    Poodle
    sub class of Dog
